th authorization2star  aThe award-winning novelist William Kennedy is perhaps best known for his Albany Cycle, a series of novels that put Albany on the world's literary map alongside James Joyce's Dublin, Gabriel García Márquez's Macondo, and William Faulkner's Yoknapatawpha County. Bootlegger of the Soul offers a fresh and authoritative overview of Kennedy's long literary career and his astonishing trajectory from journalist to struggling novelist to Pulitzer Prize winner. Included here are reviews, interviews, and scholarly essays on Kennedy's work, as well as essays, speeches, a play, and a short story by the author himself, together with more than fifty historical and personal photographs. Lively, readable, and brimming with the infectious wit and lyrical prose that animates Kennedy's novels, Bootlegger of the Soul is a celebration of a writer still working hard at his craft at age ninety.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 4aLiterature : American Literature. 4aLiterature : Literary Criticism. 4aNew York/Regional : New York/Regional. 7aLITERARY COLLECTIONS / Essays.2bisacsh1 aBeck, Stefan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrinkley, Douglas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCroyden, Margaret, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEdwards, Thomas R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFlanagan, Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGiamo, Benedict, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGillespie, Michael Patrick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrondahl, Paul, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGrumbach, Doris, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/